00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.579
watching and realized the only
thing he had ever really loved

00:04:17.579 --> 00:04:18.870
was storytelling in movies.

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:20.911
And so he thought, I'll
just show up in Hollywood

00:04:20.911 --> 00:04:22.440
and figure out how to break in.

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:23.970
So he schlepped coffee.

00:04:23.970 --> 00:04:26.580
And one of the jobs
that junior people do

00:04:26.580 --> 00:04:28.110
is to actually read scripts.

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:29.610
And he found most
of the scripts had

00:04:29.610 --> 00:04:33.300
these really trite storylines
that just kind of repeated

00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:35.160
the same heroic
architecture and didn't

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:38.316
reflect the stories that he
wanted to see in the world.

00:04:38.316 --> 00:04:39.690
And one point he
thought, there's

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:41.360
got to be a different way.

00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:43.440
So he went through his
entire Rolodex of people

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:45.750
he had met in the last
year, and literally

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:48.250
like went through and said, oh,
I saw this person for lunch,

00:04:48.250 --> 00:04:50.880
I saw this person for dinner,
and organized an 89% email

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:52.980
list under an alias--

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:56.580
Google-- and actually
sent out a note saying,

00:04:56.580 --> 00:04:59.317
if you share with me the movies
you've seen in the last year

00:04:59.317 --> 00:05:01.650
that you've loved but haven't
been put into production--

00:05:01.650 --> 00:05:05.180
excuse me, scripts, not movies--

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:07.700
I will collate it that up,
using his McKinsey skills,

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:09.229
and I will send it back to you.

00:05:09.229 --> 00:05:10.520
So that's the give and the get.

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:12.724
Do that and let's
see where it goes.

00:05:12.724 --> 00:05:13.640
And people cooperated.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:15.290
In fact they shared
it with friends.

00:05:15.290 --> 00:05:17.480
And he ended up doing
this tabulation process,

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.250
only because he wanted to find
the scripts his boss would

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:21.104
need.

00:05:21.104 --> 00:05:22.520
And the reason he
used an alias is

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:24.311
because he didn't want
his boss to think he

00:05:24.311 --> 00:05:26.180
wasn't good at his job.

00:05:26.180 --> 00:05:26.976
So he does this.

00:05:26.976 --> 00:05:29.600
This is back in the days when we
actually all went on vacation,

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:30.560
actually logged off.

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:33.050
So he printed off the top five
that he got from the master

00:05:33.050 --> 00:05:35.060
list, took off.

00:05:35.060 --> 00:05:37.910
He comes back two weeks
later and his inbox

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:42.740
full of this roll up
list, this blacklist, all

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:45.780
sent back to him saying,
this is the most amazing list

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:46.280
of scripts.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:48.320
We should all be
taking a look at it.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:51.050
And so literally hundreds
of emails are in his inbox

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:55.620
because no one knows it's him
that has started this process.

00:05:55.620 --> 00:05:57.934
Now if it was a
build, you could see

00:05:57.934 --> 00:06:00.350
that some of the movies that
have been put into production

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:03.920
because of The Black List are
"Juno" and "The King's Speech".

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:05.060
Who would imagine, right?

00:06:05.060 --> 00:06:06.560
And so these were
these scripts that

00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:10.087
were destined for the dustbin
and pulled out and put back

00:06:10.087 --> 00:06:12.170
on the master list, that
we should really consider

00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:13.800
these odd ducky stories--

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:16.590
"Moonlight".

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.870
One of the things
that Franklin did

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:20.340
is he asked a
brand-new question.

00:06:20.340 --> 00:06:23.460
And I said it in such a quick
way when I first rolled out,

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:26.490
what did he ask his people, that
it's worth kind of pausing on.

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:30.139
He asked, what movies
do you love that haven't

00:06:30.139 --> 00:06:31.180
been put into production?

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:33.262
What scripts do you love?

00:06:33.262 --> 00:06:35.470
And the reality is, that's
not how Hollywood has been

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:36.980
formatted up to this point.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:39.420
What's Hollywood sort on--

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:42.002
what will make us money.

00:06:42.002 --> 00:06:43.460
And by doing it
through an alias he

00:06:43.460 --> 00:06:44.960
actually found a
community of people

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:46.630
who cared about
the same question

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:48.920
as that, a different
kind of purpose

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:49.970
pulling people together.

00:06:49.970 --> 00:06:52.553
And it provided enough anonymity
that people could essentially

00:06:52.553 --> 00:06:54.170
vote the way their
heart felt, not

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:56.900
vote the way their boss
might want them to vote.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:01.322
And so it changed an
access of orientation.

00:07:01.322 --> 00:07:02.780
And one of the
things that shows us

00:07:02.780 --> 00:07:07.190
is really the power of
community in that process.

00:07:07.190 --> 00:07:10.280
So often we think about
power, the ability

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:11.630
to get things done, as personal.

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:13.463
And so we'll often
describe-- like Franklin,

00:07:13.463 --> 00:07:16.940
in fact, gets featured in "Fast
Company" and stuff as the guy,

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:20.720
as he changed Hollywood because
he produced The Black List.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.420
And it's a singular
hero that is carved out

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:26.300
as if it's not in context
to all the other people who

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:27.500
participated.

00:07:27.500 --> 00:07:29.134
And so surely he had
grit and surely he

00:07:29.134 --> 00:07:30.800
asked a brand-new
question and surely he

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:33.356
did absolutely an
amazing set of things.

00:07:33.356 --> 00:07:35.105
But the thing that
actually made The Black

00:07:35.105 --> 00:07:38.510
List powerful to
get that effort done

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:42.377
is a social act, a communal act.

00:07:42.377 --> 00:07:44.710
And that's community in a
different way than, let's say,

00:07:44.710 --> 00:07:46.360
how Facebook used it.

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.210
Facebook uses the term
community as a group of people

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:50.980
that we can then monetize.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:52.984
That's not an actual
community, right?

00:07:52.984 --> 00:07:54.400
Community is a
group of people who

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:57.080
are held together by
shared beliefs, a shared

00:07:57.080 --> 00:07:58.300
set of purposes.

00:07:58.300 --> 00:08:03.367
And then together they can do
things in a meaningful way.

00:08:03.367 --> 00:08:04.950
This is important
also because I think

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:06.575
it changes how we
might think about how

00:08:06.575 --> 00:08:08.220
we conceive of our work.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:10.050
Instead of thinking,
what can I do,

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:14.190
you start to think, who can I
organize around a new question?

00:08:14.190 --> 00:08:16.080
And if you walk away
with nothing else

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.200
other than that
vignette and that story,

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:20.940
it might change how we
think and conceive of how

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:23.190
we gather power in our lives.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:25.290
Because if the story's
always a singular

00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:29.620
hero on top of a magazine
cover, we miss the real point.

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:34.250
That's individuating something
that is deeply connected.

00:08:34.250 --> 00:08:36.950
Now most of us lack that
connection, that ability

00:08:36.950 --> 00:08:39.950
to kind of think about, what
is it that gives me meaning?

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:43.610
In fact 61% of us, the data
says, cover or hide ourselves

00:08:43.610 --> 00:08:44.450
at work--

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:46.610
covering being defined
as, we actually

00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:50.180
don't show up as
our true selves.

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:52.270
Some of the vignettes
in the research--

00:08:52.270 --> 00:08:54.080
a guy wearing glasses
because he didn't

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:57.247
want to look young, a young
man who didn't talk about how

00:08:57.247 --> 00:08:59.330
he wanted to be a co-parent
because he didn't want

00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:00.740
his colleagues to
think he wasn't

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:04.100
interested in his career,
and so on and so on.

00:09:04.100 --> 00:09:07.310
What was most surprising about
that detail, that 61% of us

00:09:07.310 --> 00:09:10.430
cover or hide ourselves at
work, is that it didn't just

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:12.820
affect traditional groups
of underserved and underseen

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:13.870
people.

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:16.820
45%, nearly half of
straight white men,

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:19.036
also say they cover,
which makes sense

00:09:19.036 --> 00:09:21.410
if you think about all the
different ways in which people

00:09:21.410 --> 00:09:24.860
believe they have to fit to
an archetype or some mirage

00:09:24.860 --> 00:09:28.700
of normal in order to
actually fit in at work.

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:30.560
And as long as we're
fitting in that way,

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:32.720
we're not actually
being our true selves.

00:09:32.720 --> 00:09:34.197
And from that place
of true self is

00:09:34.197 --> 00:09:36.530
where we understand what gives
us meaning, what gives us

00:09:36.530 --> 00:09:39.260
purpose, and what things we
actually care about, therefore

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:40.620
the genesis of our ideas.

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:47.740
Now this lack of social
standing-- we show up at work.

00:09:47.740 --> 00:09:50.980
Fitting in is the greatest
barrier to belonging.

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:53.500
When we lack that ability to
belong as our true selves,

00:09:53.500 --> 00:09:55.750
we also lack the ability
to generate ideas

00:09:55.750 --> 00:09:57.680
that we care about.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:01.720
I was talking with a banking
executive not so long ago.

00:10:01.720 --> 00:10:04.570
And this woman was saying she
had a really innovative idea

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:06.860
for how to change the
low end of the market,

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:09.612
how to serve the deep poor,
the people who use those cash

00:10:09.612 --> 00:10:12.070
and carry kind of places where
the check-cashing places are

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:12.670
used.

00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:15.425
They typically take between
5% and 10% of that check.

00:10:15.425 --> 00:10:17.050
And she said she had
a way for her bank

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:19.780
to serve that marketplace
with less than half a percent.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:21.217
And I was like, oh my God.

00:10:21.217 --> 00:10:23.050
You could get a whole
bunch of new customers

00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:26.482
and it would change an entire
group of people's lives, right?

00:10:26.482 --> 00:10:27.940
And she says, "Yeah,
but I'll never

00:10:27.940 --> 00:10:31.080
tell the people
sitting at this table."

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:34.000
And I looked at her with
that sort of tilt in my head.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:35.800
I thought, why would
you not say it?

00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:37.420
Why would you not own it?

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:39.940
And it wasn't hard to
think about for a second.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:41.470
She sat there and
she said, "Yeah,

00:10:41.470 --> 00:10:43.420
that person has an Hermes bag.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:45.940
That person has a
such and such tie."

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:50.290
And she said all these people
have wealthy backgrounds.

00:10:50.290 --> 00:10:52.600
And she didn't ever
want to show that she

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:54.760
didn't have that same
background, because what

00:10:54.760 --> 00:10:56.020
was she doing?

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:58.260
She was fitting in
in order to belong.

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:00.010
And as long as she was
fitting in in order

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:02.469
to belong in that
half soul kind of way,

00:11:02.469 --> 00:11:04.510
she was never also going
to claim that thing that

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:07.840
was true for her, her history
and experience, her own visions

00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:10.540
and hopes based on that
history and experience.

00:11:10.540 --> 00:11:13.930
Without social standing, we lack
the ability to actually create

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:15.730
change, real change,
the change we actually

00:11:15.730 --> 00:11:16.930
want to see in the world.

00:11:19.550 --> 00:11:22.106
Now I've written--
[? Obie ?] alluded to it.

00:11:22.106 --> 00:11:24.230
I've written two books
before on collaborative work

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:25.670
and how power should
be distributed

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:27.020
within organizations,
so basically talking

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:29.120
about flat organizations
and breaking down

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:32.039
the perimeter of organizations
to open up innovation.

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:33.830
And a lot of times
people say, well, you've

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:35.390
studied these business
models for years.

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:36.765
You've done
innovation for years.

00:11:36.765 --> 00:11:38.450
This must be why you care.

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:40.640
And actually the
real reason of why

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:44.430
I noticed this grouping problem
is because of my own heritage.

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:46.100
You see when I was
18 years old, I

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:48.700
was actually supposed to
get an arranged marriage.

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:51.909
And I had returned home in fact.

00:11:51.909 --> 00:11:54.200
When I was 18 I'd gone to
community college for the day

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:55.105
and returned home.

00:11:55.105 --> 00:11:57.730
And there my aunties and uncles
and stuff had filled the house.

00:11:57.730 --> 00:11:59.050
And if you know Indian
families, they're

00:11:59.050 --> 00:12:00.400
just all like over the place.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.980
And they had been
there to tell me

00:12:02.980 --> 00:12:05.380
that my arranged marriage
was, well, arranged,

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:08.950
and the sort of terms
of the deal were set.

00:12:08.950 --> 00:12:11.677
And I had turned to my uncle
who was sort of representing--

00:12:11.677 --> 00:12:14.260
because my father wasn't in the
picture-- who was representing

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:17.760
me, or representing our
family, and said, "So did you

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:19.790
ask the guy if I could
get an education?",

00:12:19.790 --> 00:12:21.790
because that was the only
thing I had ever said.

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:24.781
If you could please make
sure that was taken care of,

00:12:24.781 --> 00:12:25.780
I would be OK with that.

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:28.280
Because ever since I was 4 and
1/2 and moved to this country

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:31.810
I understood my job to be that
of taking care of my mother

00:12:31.810 --> 00:12:34.270
and getting this arranged
marriage as a way of serving

00:12:34.270 --> 00:12:35.497
the family.

00:12:35.497 --> 00:12:37.080
And my uncle had
turned to me and said

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:40.710
no, "She won't let me ask
because she's negotiating

00:12:40.710 --> 00:12:43.350
for a house and some other
things so her future is taken

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:44.470
care of.

00:12:44.470 --> 00:12:48.530
She doesn't want to also ask
for your needs and interests."

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:52.000
So I was polite enough
to wait until my aunties

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.560
and uncles left, and then
I turned to her, my mother,

00:12:56.560 --> 00:12:58.720
and I had done this sort
of theatrical thing, which

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:01.390
is not my style normally.

00:13:01.390 --> 00:13:04.169
And I had gone to Future
Business Leaders of America,

00:13:04.169 --> 00:13:05.710
so this sentence is
entirely informed

00:13:05.710 --> 00:13:08.650
by a Future Business Leaders
of America club in high school.

00:13:08.650 --> 00:13:11.170
And I said, "I am the product.

00:13:11.170 --> 00:13:14.350
You cannot do the
deal without me.

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:18.220
So ask the guy if I can
get an education and this

00:13:18.220 --> 00:13:19.300
will be done."

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:22.030
And I had turned the closest
thing next to me, a cardboard

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:24.550
box without a lid or
anything, like grocery box,

00:13:24.550 --> 00:13:28.420
and I grabbed it and I had
put in five books and one

00:13:28.420 --> 00:13:33.857
outfit, no toothbrush, no money,
because I didn't have any.

00:13:33.857 --> 00:13:36.190
And you can tell my priorities,
right books, one outfit.

00:13:36.190 --> 00:13:38.550
And I was just doing
this theatrical thing of,

00:13:38.550 --> 00:13:41.020
and I'm leaving unless
you change your mind.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:44.860
And I actually thought this
would end in about an hour.

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:48.640
And so I walked down the
street to the local donut shop,

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:49.690
as one does--

00:13:49.690 --> 00:13:51.770
carbohydrates, everything.

00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:55.000
And I thought I was just going
to wait it out and then call

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.890
home and be like, it's done.

00:13:56.890 --> 00:14:00.730
When I called home, the
situation only escalated, like,

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:03.190
we're never going
to change our mind.

00:14:03.190 --> 00:14:05.230
But you come home right now.

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:06.960
And one day turn into two.

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:08.170
Two days turned into three.

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:11.510
And well, it's been 30 years.

00:14:11.510 --> 00:14:15.060
And I got exited from
my family homeless,

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:20.120
uneducated, no cash in
the pocket kind of thing,

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:26.910
to go off and figure out this
new direction in my life.

00:14:26.910 --> 00:14:31.260
In that moment, my
identity was being defined.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:33.120
My value of the
world, my ability

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:35.190
to create my own
space in the world

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:37.230
was being defined by what--

00:14:37.230 --> 00:14:42.300
a group I belonged to, in this
case being an Indian or Muslim

00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:45.570
or woman, some
combination thereof, that

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:49.800
said the only value you
have to us in the world

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:54.520
is to serve in this
way, in this box.

00:14:54.520 --> 00:14:56.560
That was the first
time I saw groupings.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:59.240
And I thought, well, it's
probably true to my family.

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:01.193
But then I would go on and do--

00:15:01.193 --> 00:15:04.660
one of my first jobs was
as an admin at Apple.

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:08.290
And I showed up in one
of those early meetings .

00:15:08.290 --> 00:15:12.827
I was such an eager kid to
want to prove myself and stuff.

00:15:12.827 --> 00:15:14.410
And at one time they
said, "Hey, we're

00:15:14.410 --> 00:15:17.230
going to brainstorm about
X. Come to the meeting.

00:15:17.230 --> 00:15:18.310
We're going to do this."

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:20.800
And I remember doing all
the research I could find

00:15:20.800 --> 00:15:22.900
and formulating
questions and showing up

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:24.474
and being so excited.

00:15:24.474 --> 00:15:25.890
You can totally
picture it, right,

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:27.056
like this sort of like, yay.

00:15:27.056 --> 00:15:29.620
And it only took a minute
or two, maybe even three,

00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:33.400
to realize no one was
making eye contact with me.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:35.450
Because it turns
out in that room

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:38.320
it was the MBAs
who had the ability

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:42.640
to qualify for having ideas,
seeing through that category,

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:44.710
not for everyone.

00:15:44.710 --> 00:15:47.110
In later jobs it
would be engineers

00:15:47.110 --> 00:15:49.630
were the people we
expected to have ideas, not

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:50.830
marketing people.

00:15:50.830 --> 00:15:53.760
[? Obie, ?] you might
recognize that one.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:56.420
Or in other jobs it's only
the top executive management

00:15:56.420 --> 00:16:00.290
team is allowed to have
ideas, not this other group.

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:01.940
And so this thing
about groupings

00:16:01.940 --> 00:16:04.947
ended up showing up
throughout my career in tech,

00:16:04.947 --> 00:16:07.280
throughout all the different
ways in which I was driving

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:08.821
strategy and innovation
and realizing

00:16:08.821 --> 00:16:11.540
that's actually the biggest
limiting factor is that we're

00:16:11.540 --> 00:16:14.420
not noticing the one thing
that actually counts,

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:17.420
the individual that's
standing right in front of us,

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:22.550
invisible to some, but purely
able to offer that perspective,

00:16:22.550 --> 00:16:24.560
that idea that they have.

00:16:24.560 --> 00:16:26.310
Sometimes they're
invisible to themselves.

00:16:26.310 --> 00:16:28.610
I'm not suggesting
it's just external.

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:36.540
But it is denying the power
of the singular voice,

00:16:36.540 --> 00:16:39.530
and making invisible
that which has value

00:16:39.530 --> 00:16:44.410
simply because of the packaging,
not because of the idea.

00:16:44.410 --> 00:16:46.480
So I'll fast forward
and just point out

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:48.820
that this is actually
a trend that allows

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:50.020
us to do innovation, right?

00:16:50.020 --> 00:16:54.100
So Apple and Google helped
change the mobile marketplace.

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:58.120
I was around back when
companies like Apple or Samsung

00:16:58.120 --> 00:17:00.160
used to actually choose--

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:04.359
the term was choosing on deck
which apps they would provide,

00:17:04.359 --> 00:17:07.236
one or two or three apps costing
about $1 million to $2 million

00:17:07.236 --> 00:17:09.819
in development, probably about
the same in sales and marketing

00:17:09.819 --> 00:17:10.750
expense.

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:12.910
And those companies
would then decide,

00:17:12.910 --> 00:17:15.910
choose for the consumer-- here's
the thing they would offer.

00:17:15.910 --> 00:17:18.550
And Apple came along and
changed that developer platform

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:21.130
so it only cost $10,000
to be able to participate

00:17:21.130 --> 00:17:23.770
in that ecosystem, allowing
a marketplace of ideas

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:26.230
to happen in the form of apps.

00:17:26.230 --> 00:17:29.290
And then Google came along
and did it one better, always,

00:17:29.290 --> 00:17:33.220
and dropped it down to $500
and changed this opportunity

00:17:33.220 --> 00:17:35.800
for people to come
from everywhere

00:17:35.800 --> 00:17:37.270
and be able to participate.

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:39.160
And when I started
spotting that I was like,

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:42.820
is that a pattern that would
allow a whole bunch of people

00:17:42.820 --> 00:17:46.180
to suddenly become available
in the marketplace of ideas?

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:49.960
Could that idea transpose the
immediate of a smartphone app

00:17:49.960 --> 00:17:52.720
or a platform-based model?

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:59.584
And that's when I had actually
coined this term onlyness.

00:17:59.584 --> 00:18:01.375
Essentially it's an
economic thesis, right?

00:18:01.375 --> 00:18:04.060
It's basically arguing that
value can come from anywhere.

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:07.030
Ideas come from that spot in
the world that each of us stand.

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:08.850
They can scale in connectedness.

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:11.770
So you can see the two
parts, "only-ness".

00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:14.485
I should not go into marketing.

00:18:14.485 --> 00:18:16.150
But I was basically
arguing, this

00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:20.090
is the way in which we will
create value in the future.

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:24.100
Now I still believe this.

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:27.132
Oh, the build's
not going to work?

00:18:27.132 --> 00:18:30.120
But it's a really pretty build.

00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:36.680
The opportunity for each of
us to finally get a chance

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:40.100
to actually stand more
deeply in our own truth,

00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:41.600
and like Franklin,
be able to ask

00:18:41.600 --> 00:18:46.820
new questions of our workforce,
of our work environment,

00:18:46.820 --> 00:18:48.940
and even outside that.

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:51.730
It could change not only
what we individually do

00:18:51.730 --> 00:18:54.770
but what we're able
to create together.

00:18:54.770 --> 00:19:00.167
I think to those economists
who say we've run out of ideas,

00:19:00.167 --> 00:19:02.250
I think they've only counted
about 30 some percent

00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:05.520
of the ideas, the ideas that
come from traditional power

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:09.660
base, which in America is
mostly white and mostly male,

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:13.360
and mostly from places
that sound like "Hah-vuhd",

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:16.150
when they could actually come
from each and every single one

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:17.830
of us.

00:19:17.830 --> 00:19:21.100
In fact if I could ask you to
do one little exercise with me,

00:19:21.100 --> 00:19:26.960
close your eyes for a second
and think back to that time

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:32.150
when you first were
valued just as yourself.

00:19:32.150 --> 00:19:36.380
Somebody saw you and
said, this is who you are,

00:19:36.380 --> 00:19:40.410
and it's special, or
this is what you can do,

00:19:40.410 --> 00:19:42.350
and that's good.

00:19:42.350 --> 00:19:47.320
They saw some light in
you, some shining capacity,

00:19:47.320 --> 00:19:48.850
and wanted that to come forward.

00:19:51.830 --> 00:19:57.000
Imagine now if everyone
was given that same idea.

00:20:03.330 --> 00:20:07.950
I think that's the power of what
we can do next, that each of us

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:11.160
as we stand in that spot in
the world only we stand in,

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:13.770
we can be deeply
rooted in our purpose.

00:20:13.770 --> 00:20:15.810
And as we do that,
it will help us

00:20:15.810 --> 00:20:19.370
find the people who care about
the same things as we do.

00:20:19.370 --> 00:20:22.620
And as we do that, we end
up being able to actually

00:20:22.620 --> 00:20:25.830
shape the world around
us, to not just include

00:20:25.830 --> 00:20:27.270
those opinions
that are currently

00:20:27.270 --> 00:20:30.900
heard but the set of
opinions that are everywhere.

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:34.320
That can reshape the world
to include all of our voices

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:37.910
in a much more equal and
fair way, and also of course

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:41.070
allows the power to innovate.

00:20:41.070 --> 00:20:42.820
So that's what I came
to say and share.

00:20:42.820 --> 00:20:46.430
And the rest of the time is
really just about a chance

00:20:46.430 --> 00:20:48.800
to do Q&amp;A. And
[? Obie ?] can come

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:51.180
and-- she probably even
has a question knowing her.

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:52.600
But we'll pass
along the mic too.

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:58.400
You can ask anything from
what's it like to write a book--

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:00.500
some people like to
ask that question--

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:02.499
to-- go.

00:21:02.499 --> 00:21:03.290
SPEAKER: Excellent.

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:06.210
So just put your hand up
and I'll pass you the mic so

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:09.200
that people can hear it.

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:11.040
So I'm going to kick
off with a question.

00:21:11.040 --> 00:21:13.340
So one of the things
that intrigued me

00:21:13.340 --> 00:21:17.120
about onlyness and this
sort of relationship

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:19.100
between the individual
and the groups

00:21:19.100 --> 00:21:22.460
is that when we talk about
diversity and inclusion,

00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:25.970
we often talk about
specific groups, like women

00:21:25.970 --> 00:21:28.590
or gay people, et cetera.

00:21:28.590 --> 00:21:31.040
And as we kind of experience
at Google, that some of that

00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:33.065
can be very exclusionist
and people sort

00:21:33.065 --> 00:21:35.690
of saying, well, why are you
giving privilege to this group

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:38.210
or why did that group have
privilege in the first place,

00:21:38.210 --> 00:21:38.960
and so on.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:40.370
And so one of the things
I think is interesting

00:21:40.370 --> 00:21:42.920
about this is that you bring it
back to the individual rather

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:43.430
than the group.

00:21:43.430 --> 00:21:45.096
So can you talk a
little bit about that,

00:21:45.096 --> 00:21:47.120
what the implications
would be if we

00:21:47.120 --> 00:21:50.360
thought about diversity and
inclusion in a different way?

00:21:50.360 --> 00:21:51.710
NILOFER MERCHANT: Sure.

00:21:51.710 --> 00:21:54.800
So in fact I felt so
bad for the situation

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:57.140
that happened this summer
because it was completely

00:21:57.140 --> 00:22:00.350
predictable, that if you
start doing, oh, we're

00:22:00.350 --> 00:22:01.970
going to try to
include this group,

00:22:01.970 --> 00:22:04.970
it feels to the group on the
other side of the teeter-tot,

00:22:04.970 --> 00:22:08.630
that power is being displaced,
that they're being replaced.

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:13.144
And if we're actually talking
about a limited sum of the pie,

00:22:13.144 --> 00:22:15.560
then you understand why people
are fighting over that pie.

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:17.726
This model actually says
something different, right,

00:22:17.726 --> 00:22:19.880
which is that as you
open up the opportunity,

00:22:19.880 --> 00:22:23.010
more opportunity exists,
just like that Apple example.

00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:25.220
So let's just use a specific.

00:22:25.220 --> 00:22:27.060
In fact you helped
me find this story.

00:22:27.060 --> 00:22:29.570
So one of the stories in the
book is the story of Foldit.

00:22:29.570 --> 00:22:33.130
Does anybody know this
story by any chance?

00:22:33.130 --> 00:22:35.920
Cheater, she's read the book.

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:39.000
So Foldit is an
online platform that

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.970
was started based out of
University of Washington.

00:22:41.970 --> 00:22:45.150
And they were trying to solve
a problem in the bio sciences

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:49.650
space where if proteins
fold incorrectly,

00:22:49.650 --> 00:22:51.820
they basically cause
disease, bottom line.

00:22:51.820 --> 00:22:53.580
And so things like
Alzheimer's and stuff

00:22:53.580 --> 00:22:56.400
are all diseases caused
by misfolded proteins.

00:22:56.400 --> 00:22:58.560
And they were
realizing, this UW team,

00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:00.330
that every research
team around the world

00:23:00.330 --> 00:23:02.580
was recreating the
problem of how proteins

00:23:02.580 --> 00:23:05.340
were misfolding in order
to do the actual research

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:06.480
they wanted to do.

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:07.590
And they thought,
this is kind of silly.

00:23:07.590 --> 00:23:09.870
There ought to be like a
repository you can draw on

00:23:09.870 --> 00:23:12.090
so that the foundational
work is there

00:23:12.090 --> 00:23:14.040
and people can build
on it, therefore

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:15.270
accelerating the research.

00:23:15.270 --> 00:23:18.810
And they started an online
app to basically crowd science

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:19.620
this process.

00:23:19.620 --> 00:23:21.411
And at first they
thought, their first step

00:23:21.411 --> 00:23:23.920
was, we're going to get
PhDs from around the world.

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:26.040
So think globalization
of talent, right?

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:28.560
And that didn't turn out to
have any breakthroughs at all.

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:30.440
They let it run
for almost a year.

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:33.300
And so then they thought,
maybe there's another way.

00:23:33.300 --> 00:23:35.449
What if we actually
allow anyone?

00:23:35.449 --> 00:23:37.740
Could we actually allow
anyone, quite possibly everyone

00:23:37.740 --> 00:23:38.374
to participate?

00:23:38.374 --> 00:23:40.290
Why don't we build a
game that would teach you

00:23:40.290 --> 00:23:42.450
the fundamentals, like
basically teaching

00:23:42.450 --> 00:23:44.850
how proteins fold, and then
you can take it from there.

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:47.190
And that created more resolve.

00:23:47.190 --> 00:23:48.580
But then they
realized actually--

00:23:48.580 --> 00:23:49.470
they were sitting
there watching the game

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:52.380
and noticing that people were
crowding around the people who

00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:56.430
had degrees from certain
schools or that were men

00:23:56.430 --> 00:23:59.010
and not actually
noticing who actually

00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:01.734
was good at the
protein-folding problem.

00:24:01.734 --> 00:24:03.150
And they could
spot the difference

00:24:03.150 --> 00:24:04.560
because they themselves
had actually-- you

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:05.760
know, they were studying it.

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:06.780
And they just thought,
well what if we actually

00:24:06.780 --> 00:24:09.270
hide those social
signals and just tune

00:24:09.270 --> 00:24:12.180
them down so that if you really
want to know, you could know,

00:24:12.180 --> 00:24:15.060
but the focus is entirely on,
oh, that's working better,

00:24:15.060 --> 00:24:16.939
and people can notice that.

00:24:16.939 --> 00:24:17.730
That was one thing.

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:20.520
And then the other thing they
started to do was they actually

00:24:20.520 --> 00:24:23.130
just realized they were
rewarding individuals instead

00:24:23.130 --> 00:24:25.440
of rewarding group work.

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.932
So most work today is
complex problem solving.

00:24:27.932 --> 00:24:29.640
Complex problem solving
is not [? Obie ?]

00:24:29.640 --> 00:24:31.681
sitting by herself or
Nilofer sitting by herself.

00:24:31.681 --> 00:24:33.812
It's how we start to
play off each other.

00:24:33.812 --> 00:24:36.270
And so then as soon as they
changed the reward system to be

00:24:36.270 --> 00:24:38.811
we all win together if we all
help each other go through this

00:24:38.811 --> 00:24:40.562
thing-- they'd share
in the credit--

00:24:40.562 --> 00:24:43.020
it changed how people actually
responded in what they work.

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:45.870
And then they created
these breakthroughs.

00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:48.270
So I think the
problem is most of us

00:24:48.270 --> 00:24:50.940
have too many social
signals in the way,

00:24:50.940 --> 00:24:54.130
and we're focusing on
that instead of the work.

00:24:54.130 --> 00:24:58.960
And so I don't think about
diversity and inclusion as,

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:01.770
I want to go recruit
X number of people.

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:05.250
It's, what problems
do we have, and what

00:25:05.250 --> 00:25:06.930
is the mechanism
in place that would

00:25:06.930 --> 00:25:08.880
allow a whole bunch of
people to come and play

00:25:08.880 --> 00:25:10.150
with that problem?

00:25:10.150 --> 00:25:13.417
So if I'm really practical, when
I was doing consulting work,

00:25:13.417 --> 00:25:15.000
one of the things
we would do is go in

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:18.070
and we'd signed a
contract with the company

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:20.070
and say we're going to
help you solve X problem.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:22.800
And this is typically after
they had failed at it themselves

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:24.900
and hired a BCG or
McKinsey or whatever

00:25:24.900 --> 00:25:26.070
and failed at it with them.

00:25:26.070 --> 00:25:28.080
And then we were in the
room and we would say,

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:30.090
we're going to be in
charge of the process.

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:31.923
They would of course
nod their head because,

00:25:31.923 --> 00:25:34.320
by the way, who wants to be
in charge of the process,

00:25:34.320 --> 00:25:36.597
and completely signed off
to that, without a thought.

00:25:36.597 --> 00:25:38.430
And then the first day
we'd say, well, we're

00:25:38.430 --> 00:25:41.250
going to send out an email
to anyone at the company,

00:25:41.250 --> 00:25:43.250
as broad a group as
possible, sometimes

00:25:43.250 --> 00:25:44.800
the entire company
roster, and say,

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:47.885
anybody who wants to come
help us with this can come.

00:25:47.885 --> 00:25:50.010
And they would always have
this total look of panic

00:25:50.010 --> 00:25:51.870
go across their
face, like I don't

00:25:51.870 --> 00:25:54.600
want the ad man or the
salesperson who's not happy

00:25:54.600 --> 00:25:56.886
or the--

00:25:56.886 --> 00:25:58.260
it's almost like
the thought that

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:00.770
would go through their head
is, I don't want the crazy.

00:26:00.770 --> 00:26:02.130
And I'm putting that in air
quotes for a reason, right?

00:26:02.130 --> 00:26:04.620
I don't want the crazy or
the wild one in the room

00:26:04.620 --> 00:26:06.690
because we have
a process to run.

00:26:06.690 --> 00:26:09.310
And I'm like, trust us,
we'll actually get there.

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:13.544
And as soon as you can have all
that difference around the room

00:26:13.544 --> 00:26:15.960
and allow each difference to
actually have their own voice

00:26:15.960 --> 00:26:18.000
or create the space for that--

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.680
so it could be sometimes
we had Post-its

00:26:19.680 --> 00:26:21.680
and let people have their
ideas and it turns out

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:24.300
the Post-its came from a person
who had relatively low power.

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:28.510
But as soon as you disassociated
the power status to the idea,

00:26:28.510 --> 00:26:30.509
you could see the
idea for what it was.

00:26:30.509 --> 00:26:32.550
Then all of a sudden two,
three, four weeks later

00:26:32.550 --> 00:26:33.650
we'd have this
breakthrough in the room.

00:26:33.650 --> 00:26:34.590
And it always--

00:26:34.590 --> 00:26:36.960
I mean always, I say
this universally--

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:41.700
came from that crazy and
wild person in the room.

00:26:41.700 --> 00:26:45.330
And so how do we do that then
for all of our organizations?

00:26:45.330 --> 00:26:48.790
How do we actually start to
go take down the signals,

00:26:48.790 --> 00:26:49.380
tune it down?

00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:51.519
So how do we recruit
engineering people

00:26:51.519 --> 00:26:53.310
without knowing that
they're a women first?

00:26:53.310 --> 00:26:55.620
The data says that if
we don't know that,

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:57.610
we're more likely to
use that person's code.

00:26:57.610 --> 00:27:00.750
So how do we just engineer
more in the system a way

00:27:00.750 --> 00:27:04.070
to tune down social signals?

00:27:04.070 --> 00:27:05.670
And so that easy,
practical thing

00:27:05.670 --> 00:27:08.872
of using Post-its in a
room to generate ideas

00:27:08.872 --> 00:27:10.830
instead of going around
the room, because we're

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:13.140
more likely to dismiss an
idea based on power status,

00:27:13.140 --> 00:27:14.372
would be an easy one.

00:27:14.372 --> 00:27:16.830
There's probably a hundred of
those methods that could just

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:20.850
be streamlined into the business
that would allow us to actually

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:22.590
see and contribute those ideas.

00:27:22.590 --> 00:27:25.770
Soon as you focus on the
ideas and not on the person,

00:27:25.770 --> 00:27:27.710
I think we start
to change things.

