NILOFER MERCHANT: Bridget.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:32.810
AUDIENCE: If most
of the conversation

00:28:32.810 --> 00:28:34.957
has been centered around
your professional life,

00:28:34.957 --> 00:28:36.290
how can you catch this early on?

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:38.940
So I'm thinking about my
little sister who's in college.

00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:41.480
When I went to visit her,
I was disturbed again

00:28:41.480 --> 00:28:43.767
by the amount of
Greek life and kind

00:28:43.767 --> 00:28:46.100
of like the groupthink that
centers around that and kind

00:28:46.100 --> 00:28:48.980
of like, how can I help her
unlock her onlyness early on?

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:52.370
That's my question,
stay away from it?

00:28:52.370 --> 00:28:54.144
Have fun, but not too much?

00:28:54.144 --> 00:28:56.060
NILOFER MERCHANT: So I
think one of the things

00:28:56.060 --> 00:28:57.560
is it early on in life
we're often trying

00:28:57.560 --> 00:28:58.880
to figure out how to fit in.

00:28:58.880 --> 00:29:00.890
So we're actually giving up
ourselves along that process

00:29:00.890 --> 00:29:02.973
and we're just doing it
for basic survival, right?

00:29:02.973 --> 00:29:04.940
So in Maslow's
hierarchy of needs,

00:29:04.940 --> 00:29:07.340
the bottom two levels are
the food, shelter things.

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:09.450
The top two levels are
about self-expression

00:29:09.450 --> 00:29:12.020
and self-actualization, which
is where ideas come from.

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:15.260
In the middle is this big block,
the biggest block of the thing,

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:16.761
and it's belonging.

00:29:16.761 --> 00:29:18.260
So the question is,
do we understand

00:29:18.260 --> 00:29:20.654
how to find people who care
about the same things as us?

00:29:20.654 --> 00:29:22.070
Most of us are
actually socialized

00:29:22.070 --> 00:29:25.419
to look and say, OK, where
are people already gathered?

00:29:25.419 --> 00:29:27.710
And then do we join in without
much intentional thought

00:29:27.710 --> 00:29:31.220
about, that's not
really my people, right?

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:34.400
And so this question about
who are we to one another

00:29:34.400 --> 00:29:36.180
is a question we
need to learn to ask,

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:38.971
like who am I in this mix, and
then who are we to one another?

00:29:38.971 --> 00:29:40.470
And if you're asking
yourself, gosh,

00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:42.136
I really don't feel
like I belong here--

00:29:42.136 --> 00:29:44.030
maybe your sister
really loves it, right--

00:29:44.030 --> 00:29:46.900
but to ask that and learn
that skill about who am I

00:29:46.900 --> 00:29:47.900
in relationship to this.

00:29:47.900 --> 00:29:50.725
And I had a young
entrepreneur who

00:29:50.725 --> 00:29:52.100
I think she was
like 20 something

00:29:52.100 --> 00:29:53.433
when she asked me this question.

00:29:53.433 --> 00:29:56.690
And she said she
had gotten her PhD.

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:59.180
She taught-- this was a
very accomplished young

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:00.880
entrepreneur--

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:04.670
was a yoga fanatic, and
had a boyfriend that she

00:30:04.670 --> 00:30:06.050
was thinking about marrying.

00:30:06.050 --> 00:30:08.330
And she said, "In order for
me to decide what's next,

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:10.163
which of these four
things do I have to cut?

00:30:10.163 --> 00:30:11.840
Should I quit teaching?

00:30:11.840 --> 00:30:13.880
Do I quit doing my
entrepreneurial stuff

00:30:13.880 --> 00:30:15.265
that my PhD is based on?

00:30:15.265 --> 00:30:16.640
Do I stop all of
my relationships

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:18.200
because that's
such a distraction?

00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:21.350
And should I quit yogi
stuff because that's also

00:30:21.350 --> 00:30:22.170
a distraction?"

00:30:22.170 --> 00:30:25.190
And I was like, "Why
don't you do all four

00:30:25.190 --> 00:30:29.150
and live in the Venn diagram
of everything that is you?"

00:30:29.150 --> 00:30:31.310
And maybe because she
was actually doing really

00:30:31.310 --> 00:30:34.070
cutting-edge science
stuff which allows a cell

00:30:34.070 --> 00:30:37.220
to act like a heart,
and so on-- so it

00:30:37.220 --> 00:30:39.980
has really strong ethical
implications for if you

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:44.150
can grow things from nothing.

00:30:44.150 --> 00:30:46.940
And I said, "Maybe it's your
yogi sense that will actually

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:49.957
help guide your ethical
usage of this stuff

00:30:49.957 --> 00:30:52.040
because it will remind you
of how connected we are

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:53.630
and what those decisions are.

00:30:53.630 --> 00:30:55.934
Maybe your relationship
to your students

00:30:55.934 --> 00:30:57.350
will remind you
that you're trying

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.630
to teach the next generation
about those same set

00:30:59.630 --> 00:31:02.691
of ethical implications, not
just the pure science of it,"

00:31:02.691 --> 00:31:03.190
and so on.

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:04.820
